Kilifi North MP Gideon Mung&rsquo;aro is to be installed as a Mijikenda elder, effectively becoming the Coast&rsquo;s new kingpin, a source close to the MP has disclosed.Mungaro&rsquo;s ambition and elevation will heighten the rivalry between him and Mombasa Governor Hassan Joho of ODM, long viewed as the Coast&rsquo;s supremo.He is expected to be installed soon before President Uhuru Kenyatta visits next month, but the date has not been announced.The source told the Star Mung&rsquo;aro has held a series of meetings with Mijikenda elders to sell his agenda. Mung&rsquo;aro could not be reached by press time.The Kaya elders and the Jubilee-allied leaders are expected to witness his elevation at Tononoka.Mung&rsquo;aro believes he is the person to deliver the Coast votes to Jubilee. In 2017, he will run against Kilifi Governor Amason Kingi.The source said preparations are advanced.&ldquo;Our aim is to make Mung&rsquo;aro the Coast kingpin. We are confident he will deliver not only to Kilifi, but to the entire region,&rsquo;&rsquo; he said.He said Mung&rsquo;aro has received a positive response from the elders who believe it is high time the region worked with the government to spur development.The elders are comfortable with Mung&rsquo;aro as the right link to government and person for the job, he said.During the Malindi by-election in March, Mung&rsquo;aro campaigned for Jubilee candidate Phillip Charo; however, ODM&rsquo;s Willy Mtengo won.Political observers viewed the by-election as a contest between Mung&rsquo;aro and Joho with regard to Coast supremacy. At that time Joho was seen to have overcome the first hurdle in his quest to be the region&rsquo;s undisputed leader.